&lt;p&gt;People like to make hay about &lt;a href=&quot;https://facebook.github.io/jsx/&quot;&gt;JSX&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Don‚Äôt get your undies in a bunched. All it does is make these two lines equivalent:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;gatsby-highlight&quot;&gt;
      &lt;pre class=&quot;language-jsx&quot;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token comment&quot;&gt;// No-JSX&lt;/span&gt;
React&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token function&quot;&gt;createElement&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token string&quot;&gt;&quot;h1&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;token string&quot;&gt;&quot;Hello üéÑ&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class=&quot;token comment&quot;&gt;// YAAAAS!!!-JSX&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;token tag&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token tag&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;h1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Hello üéÑ&lt;span class=&quot;token tag&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token tag&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;/&lt;/span&gt;h1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;How does HTML work in JavaScript?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Don‚Äôt think of it like HTML, it isn‚Äôt.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;JSX is just a authoring nice-to-have.
But it‚Äôs not something that works in the browser.
It must be transformed to &lt;code&gt;React.createElement()&lt;/code&gt; calls before the browser can run it.
Most apps use projects like &lt;a href=&quot;http://babeljs.io/&quot;&gt;Babel&lt;/a&gt; or
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.typescriptlang.org/&quot;&gt;TypeScript&lt;/a&gt; to handle that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Why JSX?&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;JSX is optional but it has community consensus.
There‚Äôs a certain harmony to spec‚Äôing React elements in a syntax similar to HTML.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Gotchas&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;JSX isn‚Äôt all ü¶Ñs and üåàs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lowercase attributes like &lt;code&gt;class&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;onclick&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;autofocus&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;tabindex&lt;/code&gt; become camelCased &lt;code&gt;className&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;onClick&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;autoFocus&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;tabIndex&lt;/code&gt; respectively.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They can also take any JavaScript expression.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This takes time to get used to.
The examples below are identical.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;HTML&lt;/h4&gt;
